MFCC (Mel-Frequency Cepstral Coefficients) and spectral contrast features are commonly used in audio signal processing and are often extracted as part of feature engineering for tasks like speech recognition, speaker identification, and audio classification. 

MFCCs (Mel-Frequency Cepstral Coefficients):
MFCCs are coefficients that represent the short-term power spectrum of a sound. They are derived from the Fourier transform of the audio signal, followed by a mel-frequency scaling and logarithmic compression.
The MFCCs capture information about the frequency content of the audio signal, emphasizing characteristics that are important for human auditory perception.
In the context of your project, you've extracted 13 MFCCs (mfcc_1 to mfcc_13) from each audio clip. Each MFCC coefficient provides information about different frequency bands in the audio.


Spectral Contrast:
Spectral contrast is another set of features that describe the spectral characteristics of an audio signal.
These features quantify the difference in magnitude between peaks and valleys in the spectrum, providing information about the spectral texture and timbre of the sound.
In your extracted features, you have spectral contrast features (spectral_contrast_1 to spectral_contrast_7). Each spectral contrast coefficient represents a different aspect of the spectral texture and can be used to distinguish different types of audio signals or analyze changes in spectral content over time.
