Normalization or scaling the dataset involves adjusting the values of the features in the dataset to a similar scale. This is important because many machine learning algorithms perform better when the features are on a similar scale, as it prevents features with large magnitudes from dominating those with smaller magnitudes. Normalization and scaling techniques include:

Min-Max Scaling: This technique scales the features to a fixed range, usually between 0 and 1. It is calculated by subtracting the minimum value of the feature and then dividing by the range (maximum value - minimum value).

Standardization (Z-score normalization): This technique scales the features so that they have a mean of 0 and a standard deviation of 1. It is calculated by subtracting the mean of the feature and then dividing by the standard deviation.

Robust Scaling: This technique is similar to Min-Max Scaling but uses the interquartile range (IQR) instead of the range. It is less affected by outliers compared to Min-Max Scaling.

Normalization: This technique scales each feature so that the Euclidean norm of each data point is 1. It is useful when the magnitude of the features is not important, but the direction is.

Log Transformation: This technique applies a logarithmic function to the features, which can help in handling skewed distributions and reducing the impact of outliers.

Feature Scaling to Unit Length: This technique scales each feature vector to have a Euclidean length of 1. It is often used in algorithms that rely on the dot product, such as support vector machines (SVMs).
